width="500" height="500" alt="title" /> [[Begin->Introduction]] You have a mother and father who are both accountants. They both grew up Buddhists, and although now they don't actively practice the religion, they still hold unto some of the religious guideline. You also have an a brother who is 10 years older than you. When you enter middle school, he comes out as gay to you and your parents. Your parents were not happy with his decision and said that they would not accept him as who he is. Your brother now lives in the United States for his job and keeps little contact with you and your parents. [[go back to start of life->yes]] In China, identifying as LGBTQ+ is difficult. Many families dissaprove of their children identifying as LGBTQ+, and the Chinese government does little to protect the LGBTQ+ community. These conditions create a difficult environment for a person to come out as gay. [[go back to start of life->yes]] You have enetered middle school and you are getting along with your classmates. You have a friend group, and they make you happy. However, you feel like you are different from them and the rest of your classmates. Sometimes, you feel like you want to be more than friends with the same gender. Let's go back to your life in [[America]] You express your feelings to your parents, hoping they will understand, but instead your parents become worried. They tell you they don't want you to end up like your older brother. You are sad because you thought your parents would be a little compassionate, but they almost seem angry at you for having these feelings. You go through middle school feeling like you parents don't care about your sexuality. Your lack of trust for your parents cause you to become distant to them and your friend group. Rumors start to go around that you might be gay. Middle school flies by and now [[you enter high school->high school version 1]] You feel like you are close with your school friends so you confide in them. You tell them that sometimes you feel like you are different from them and the rest of you classmates. Your friends don't understand what you are trying to say. You try to explain to them your feelings, but the more you explain the more weirded out they get. Your friends begin to distance themselves from you, and they start telling your classmates that you might be gay. You go into [[high school->high school version 1]] feeling betrayed and like you have no one. You decide these feelings you are having are just a phase so you don't tell anyone about them. You go through middle school, hanging out with the same friends. No one thinks of you weirdly. You graduate from middle school still having these same feelings that you thought you would grow out of. Now it's time for [[high school->highschool version 2]]You enter into high school known as the weird kid. You ended up going to the same high school as a lot of people from your middle school. You become really good friends with one person, but you think it's because they don't know that you're gay. To your life in [[America->America 2]] You enter into high school with your sexuality still hidden, but it's getting harder to hide it. You feel like you have to tell someone about your feelings, but you are also scared about judgement. To your life in [[America->America 2.2]] You decide to.. I'm good. Do you have time to talk right now?" "Yeah, I have time...what about?" The cultural environment that they were raised in, and everyone in their generation, is dissaproving of the LGBTQ+ community." "So should I just distance myself from them like you did?" "*sighs* I think that my biggest regret in life is not keeping our parents in my life. I wish I could call them every week and tell them about my life in America. I'm not going to tell you what to do because it's your life, but I hope that you keep our parents in your life. I have to go now, but call me more often!" "Yeah, of course! Bye." "Bye $name." [[You get married to the love of your life->get married 3]]This game was designed to compare the life of someone who is gay growing up in China to the same person growing up in America. Of course, this scenario isn't the same for everyone. There are many LGBTQ+ individuals in America that are scared to come out in fear of being judged by their parents and those around them. Also, in China, people are slowly becoming more accepting of the LGBTQ+ community. I just wanted to show that right now in China, it is less accepting to identify as LGBTQ+ than in America due to various reasons, one of them being Chinese culture. I hope my game was able to shine a light on the differences, and that you enjoyed playing it. You and your partner have a small wedding. Your parents attend, and your older brother flies in from America to attend as well. A few years after getting married, you and your partner adopt a child. You are genuinely happy, being surrounded by people who love and accept you for you. Back to your life in [[America->America 4.2]] You are born September 18th, 2015 in Brooklyn to a middle income family. You have a mom, dad, and older brother. Your parents are happy to have another child. [[Let's go back to your life in China->middle school]] You have enetered middle school and you are getting along with your classmates. You have a friend group, and they make you happy. One day after school, you are hanging out with your friends and you realize that you have a crush on someone of the same gender. You have seen same-sex couples before, but you are still confused so you talk to your parents about it. Your parents explain to you that this isn't abnormal, and that you should be accepting of your true self. They also make sure you know that they love you. Back to your life in [[China->Middle School in China]] Growing up in China, you decide how you want to deal with these feelings. [[Talk to your parents->talk to parents about it]] [[Talk to your friends->talk to friends about it]] [[Keep your feelings to yourself->keep to yourself about it]]Right before graduating middle school, you tell your friends that you are gay. They are understanding because they don't think it's weird to identify as LGBTQ+. On the streets of New York and in media, you and your classmates are constantly exposed to LGBTQ+ content. You enter high school confident in your sexuality and not trapped. Everyone knows you are gay, and although there are a couple of kids who are uncomfortable by it, the people you surround yourself with are happy to have you as a friend. [[keep your feelings bottled in->life version 1]] [[tell your parents about how you feel again->life version 2]]You have been releasing queer interactive fictions for a few years now, and one day you recieve a passionate email about one of your games. The sender tells you how amazing your game is, and how it helped them realize their own sexuality. The sender asks if they could meet you, and you email back thanking them and agreeing to meet. You meet with the sender at a coffee shop, and you end up really liking this person. You end up dating, and although this isn't the first person you've dated of the same gender, you can tell that this one is going to last. After two years of dating you get married, and after that you and your partner adopt two kids. You are happy.
